<setup>
  <selectFromSequence name = "a" from = "-7" to = "7" step = "2" exclude="-1 1"/>
  <selectFromSequence name = "b" from = "8" to = "12" step = "1"/>
  <selectFromSequence name = "c" from = "2" to = "3" step = "1" exclude="$a"/> 

  <selectFromSequence name = "s" from = "-1" to = "1" step = "2"/> 
  
  <function name="f">$s*$b*x + $a*sin(x)</function>
  <derivative name="fP">$f</derivative>
  <derivative name="fPP">$fP</derivative>
  
</setup>  

<p>
  Consider the function <m>f(x) = <math simplify>$s*$b*x + $a*sin(x)</math></m>.
</p>  

<p>
  <ol marker="a.">
    <li>
      <p>
        Find <m>f'(x)</m> and <m>f''(x)</m>. 
      </p> 
      <p>
        <m>f'(x) = </m><answer>$fP</answer>
      </p>
      <p>
        <m>f''(x) = </m><answer>$fPP</answer>
      </p>  
    </li>  
    <li>
      <p>Recall that for any value of <m>x</m>, <m>-1 \le \cos(x) \le 1</m>.  This tells us that 
      </p>
      <p>
        <answer>-abs($a)</answer> <m>\le <math simplify>abs($a)</math> \cos(x) \le </m> <answer>abs($a)</answer>.
      </p>  
      <p>
        Using this fact along with our formula for <m>f'(x)</m>, we see that 
        <m>f'(x)</m> is <answer><choiceInput inline>
          <choice>?</choice>
          <choice credit="$$fP(0) > 0">always positive</choice>
          <choice credit="$$fP(0) < 0">always negative</choice>
          <choice credit="0">sometimes negative and sometimes positive</choice>
          <choice credit="0">always zero</choice>
        </choiceInput></answer>, 
        which implies that <m>f(x)</m> is <answer><choiceInput inline>
          <choice>?</choice>
          <choice credit="$$fP(0) > 0">always increasing</choice>
          <choice credit="$$fP(0) < 0">always decreasing</choice>
          <choice credit="0">sometimes increasing and sometimes decreasing</choice>
          <choice credit="0">constant</choice>
        </choiceInput></answer>.
      </p>  
    </li> 
    <li>
      <p>
        Look at your formula for <m>f''(x)</m> from (a), and think about the behavior of this function.  Because <m>f''(x)</m> <answer><choiceInput inline>
          <choice>?</choice>
          <choice credit="0">is always positive</choice>
          <choice credit="0">is always negative</choice>
          <choice credit="1">changes sign infinitely many times</choice>
          <choice credit="0">is always zero</choice>
        </choiceInput></answer>, it follows that <m>f(x)</m> <answer><choiceInput inline>
          <choice>?</choice>
          <choice credit="0">has infinitely many relative maxima</choice>
          <choice credit="0">has infinitely many relative mimima</choice>
          <choice credit="0">is linear</choice>
          <choice credit="1">has infinitely many inflection points</choice>
        </choiceInput></answer>.
      </p>        
    </li>
  </ol>  
</p>